sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M45101
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Composite biobrick intended to induce biofilm formation in the presence of lactose. Made from parts
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Using a LacZ operon (with RBS in sequence), curli genes are expressed and ultimately induce biofilm formation. The intent of this biobrick is to turn on biofilm formation in the presence of lactose. This allows bacteria to be cultured normally and then seeded as a biofilm when lactose is added. Biofilms have a specialized metabolism and are more resilient to toxins, improving the ability for bioremediation of toxins.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Mitchell Bullough
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: made from combining parts BBa_J33207, BBa_K342003, and BBa_B0015.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Lactose can be common in some media. Lactose can also contaminate some media. If biofilms form prematurely, consider another operon.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J33207
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part (submitted in pSB1A2) consists of the lac promoter and lacZ' gene, encoding the N-terminal 76 amino acid residues of LacZ, sufficient to complement the lacZ-delta-M15 mutation for blue-white selection on Xgal plates. A SacI site has been introduced at the 3' end, overlapping the XbaI site of the Biobrick prefix. This is designed to be used as a cloning vector for making new biobricks. PCR primers can be designed with a SacI site in one primer and an SpeI site in the other. This removes the necessity for an excessively long non-complementary tail on one primer bearing either the full biobrick prefix or suffix. The PCR product can then be digested with SacI and SpeI for insertion into this plasmid, replacing the Plac-lacZ' cassette. Recombinant plasmids will then be white on IPTG/Xgal plates, whereas any that still contain the original insert will be blue. We have used this strategy to prepare several biobricks, including BBa_J33204, which contains the xylE gene encoding catechol-2,3-dioxygenase. (For making biobricks that contain lacZ', BBa_J33204 can be used in the same way; in this case, clones with plasmids that still contain xylE will turn yellow on addition of a drop of 10 mM catechol.)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA was amplified from E. coli BL21 genomic DNA using primers based on published sequence (Genbank accession J01636, gi:146575). The annotation shown here is based on that associated with this Genbank entry. The sequence shown here is derived by sequencing the construct.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Note that the SacI site overlaps the SpeI site. The Biobrick prefix ends ...TCTAGAG. When this is added to the CTC at the start of the sequence shown here, the SacI site, GAGCTC, is generated.
